    <body>
      <pb n="665"/>
      <cb n="1"/>
      <salute rend="indent">
        <lb/>Mr. <hi rend="sc">Urban</hi>, </salute>
      <dateline rend="align-right"><hi rend="italic">Bath</hi>, <hi rend="italic">June</hi> 12. </dateline>
      <p>
        <lb/><hi rend="dc(2)">I</hi>N anſwer to a correſpondent in <lb/>p. 384, I recollect ſome
        account of <lb/>one Oliver, a viper-catcher, in Bath, <lb/>who ſuffered himſelf to be bitten
        by a <lb/>viper ſeveral times in the preſence of <lb/>Dr. Mortimer, and ſeveral other phyſi-
        <lb/>cians there; and inſtantly cured the bite <lb/>by <hi rend="italic">rubbing</hi> the
        part with ſweet oil. A dog <lb/>was bitten at the ſame time, and cured <lb/>by the part
        being well rubbed with <lb/>ſweet oil. Another dog was bitten, <lb/>and died, not being
        rubbed with ſweet <cb n="2"/>
        <lb/>oil. I think it was about 25 or 30 <lb/>years ago. I have known many per- <lb/>ſons
        cured ſince by rubbing with ſweet <lb/>oil. The fat of the viper, or perhaps <lb/>any other
        oil, might do as well. I think <lb/>this account was publiſhed in your <lb/>Magazine <note
          n="*" place="bottom" rend="size(0.8) align-center">* See vol. VIII. p. 416. <hi rend="sc"
            >Edit.</hi>
        </note>; and alſo in a ſeparate pam- <lb/>phlet, and in the Philoſophical Tranſ-
        <lb/>actions. </p>
      <signed rend="align-right">D. </signed>
    </body>
